Shyft Core :: Shyft Kyc Contract      |      | This contract is the nucleus of all of the Shyft stack. This current v1 version has basic functionality for upgrading and connects to the Shyft Cache Graph via Routing for further system expansion.      |      | It should be noted that all payable functions should utilize revert, as they are dealing with assets.      |      | \"Bip32X\" & Synthetics - Here we're using an extension of the Bip32 standard that effectively uses a hash of contract address & \"chainId\" to allow any erc20/erc223 contract to allow assets to move through Shyft's opt-in compliance rails.      | Ex. Ethereum = 60      | Shyft Network = 7341      |      | This contract is built so that when the totalSupply is asked for, much like transfer et al., it only references the ShyftTokenType. For getting the native balance of any specific Bip32X token, you'd call \"getTotalSupplyBip32X\" with the proper contract address.      |      | \"Auto Migration\"      | This contract was built with the philosophy that while there needs to be *some* upgrade path, unilaterally changing the existing contract address for Users is a bad idea in practice. Instead, we use a versioning system with the ability for users to set flags to automatically upgrade their liquidity on send into this particular contract, to any other contracts that have been updated so far (in a recursive manner).      |      | Auto-Migration of assets flow:      | 1. registry contract is set up      | 2. upgrade is called by registry contract      | 3. calls to fallback looks to see if upgrade is set      | 4. if so it asks the registry for the current contract address      | 5. it then uses the \"migrateFromKycContract\", which on the receiver's end will update the _to address passed in with the progression and now has the value from the \"migrateFromKycContract\"'s payable and thus the native fuel, to back the token increase to the _to's account.      |      |      | What's Next (V2 notes):      |      | \"Shyft Safe\" - timelocked assets that will work with Byfrost      | \"Shyft Byfrost\" - economic finality bridge infrastructure      |      | Compliance Channels:      | Addresses that only accept kyc input should be able to receive packages by the bridge that are only kyc'd across byfrost.      | Ultimate accountability chain could be difficult, though a hash map of critical ipfs resources of chain data could suffice.      | This would be the same issue as data accountability by trying to leverage multiple chains for data sales as well.","events":{"EVT_Bip32X_TypeTokenFallback(address,address,uint256,uint256,uint256)":{"details":"Event for getting an erc223 asset inbound to this contract."},"EVT_WithdrawToAddress(address,address,uint256)":{"details":"Event for withdraw to address."},"EVT_WithdrawToExternalContract(address,address,uint256)":{"details":"Event for withdraw to external contract (w/ Erc223 fallbacks)."},"EVT_WithdrawToShyftKycContract(address,address,uint256)":{"details":"Event for withdraw to a specific shyft smart contract."},"EVT_migrateFromContract(address,uint256,uint256,uint256)":{"details":"Event for migration to another shyft kyc contract (from lower or equal version)."},"EVT_migrateToKycContract(address,uint256,address,address,uint256)":{"details":"Event for migration to another shyft kyc contract (of higher or equal version)."},"EVT_receivedNativeBalance(address,uint256)":{"details":"Event for receipt of native assets."}},"kind":"dev","methods":{"allowance(address,address)":{"details":"Get the current allowance for the basic Shyft token type. @dev | Shyft Core :: Shyft Kyc Contract
      |
      | This contract is the nucleus of all of the Shyft stack. This current v1 version has basic functionality for upgrading and connects to the Shyft Cache Graph via Routing for further system expansion.
      |
      | It should be noted that all payable functions should utilize revert, as they are dealing with assets.
      |
      | "Bip32X" & Synthetics - Here we're using an extension of the Bip32 standard that effectively uses a hash of contract address & "chainId" to allow any erc20/erc223 contract to allow assets to move through Shyft's opt-in compliance rails.
      | Ex. Ethereum = 60
      | Shyft Network = 7341
      |
      | This contract is built so that when the totalSupply is asked for, much like transfer et al., it only references the ShyftTokenType. For getting the native balance of any specific Bip32X token, you'd call "getTotalSupplyBip32X" with the proper contract address.
      |
      | "Auto Migration"
      | This contract was built with the philosophy that while there needs to be *some* upgrade path, unilaterally changing the existing contract address for Users is a bad idea in practice. Instead, we use a versioning system with the ability for users to set flags to automatically upgrade their liquidity on send into this particular contract, to any other contracts that have been updated so far (in a recursive manner).
      |
      | Auto-Migration of assets flow:
      | 1. registry contract is set up
      | 2. upgrade is called by registry contract
      | 3. calls to fallback looks to see if upgrade is set
      | 4. if so it asks the registry for the current contract address
      | 5. it then uses the "migrateFromKycContract", which on the receiver's end will update the _to address passed in with the progression and now has the value from the "migrateFromKycContract"'s payable and thus the native fuel, to back the token increase to the _to's account.
      |
      |
      | What's Next (V2 notes):
      |
      | "Shyft Safe" - timelocked assets that will work with Byfrost
      | "Shyft Byfrost" - economic finality bridge infrastructure
      |
      | Compliance Channels:
      | Addresses that only accept kyc input should be able to receive packages by the bridge that are only kyc'd across byfrost.
      | Ultimate accountability chain could be difficult, though a hash map of critical ipfs resources of chain data could suffice.
      | This would be the same issue as data accountability by trying to leverage multiple chains for data sales as well.

@param _nativeBip32X_type The native Bip32X type of this network. Ethereum is 60, Shyft is 7341, etc.
 @dev Invoke the constructor for ShyftSafe, which sets the owner and nativeBip32X_type class variables

@dev Gets the native bip32x token (should correspond to "chainid")
 @return result the native bip32x token (should correspond to "chainid")

@dev Removes the owner (creator of this contract)'s control completely. Functions such as linking the registry & cachegraph (& shyftSafe's setBridge), and importantly initializing this as a byfrost contract, are triggered by the owner, and as such a setting phase and afterwards triggering this function could be seen as a completely appropriate workflow.
 @return true if the owner is removed successfully
@dev mutex locks transactions ordering so that multiple chained calls cannot complete out of order.

@dev This fallback function applies value to nativeBip32X_type Token (Ether on Ethereum, Shyft on Shyft Network, etc). It also uses auto-upgrade logic so that users can automatically have their coins in the latest wallet (if everything is opted in across all contracts by the user).

@param _autoUpgrade Whether the tokens should be automatically upgraded when sent to this contract.
 @dev Sets auto upgrade for the message sender, for fallback functionality to upgrade tokens on receipt. The only reason a user would want to call this function is to modify behaviour *after* this contract has been updated, thus allowing choice.

returns._0: the balance of the SHFT token type for the user

getTotalSupplyBip32X(uint256).details: Gets the total supply for a specific bip32x token.

returns.balance: the number of tokens of that specific bip32x type in this contract

kycSend(address,uint256,uint256,bool,boo.details: | Performs a "kyc send", which is an automatic search between addresses for counterparty relationships within Trust Channels (whos rules dictate accessibility for auditing/enforcement/jurisdiction/etc.). If there is a match, the designated amount of assets is sent to the recipient.      | As there are accessor methods to check whether or not the counterparty's cachegraph is "dirty", there is little need to pass a "true" unless the transaction is critical (eg. DeFi atomic flash wrap) and there is a chance that there will need to be a unification pass before the transaction can pass with full assurety.

params._amount: The amount of assets that will be sent.
params._bip32X_type: The bip32X type of the assets that will be sent. These are synthetic (wrapped) assets, based on atomic locking.
params._identifiedAddress: The public address for the recipient to send assets (tokens) to.
params._payForDirty: Whether the sender will pay the additional cost to unify a cachegraph's relationships (if not, it will not complete).
params._requiredConsentFromAllParties: Whether to match the routing algorithm on the "consented" layer which indicates 2 way buy in of counterparty's attestation(s)

returns.result: | 0 = not enough balance to send    | 1 = consent required    | 2 = transfer cannot be processed due to transfer rules    | 3 = successful transfer

migrateFromKycContract(address).details: | Migrates the user's assets from another Shyft Kyc Contract. The following conditions have to pass:      | a) message sender is a shyft kyc contract,      | b) sending shyft kyc contract is not of a later version than this one      | c) user on this shyft kyc contract have no restrictions on only accepting KYC input (will ease in v2)

params._to: The user's address to migrate to.

returns.result: | true = migration completed successfully    | [revert] = reverts on any situation that fails on the above parameters

name().details: Gets the name of the token.

removeOwner().details: Removes the owner (creator of this contract)'s control completely. Functions such as linking the registry & cachegraph (& shyftSafe's setBridge), and importantly initializing this as a byfrost contract, are triggered by the owner, and as such a setting phase and afterwards triggering this function could be seen as a completely appropriate workflow.

returns._0: true if the owner is removed successfully

setAutoUpgrade(bool).details: Sets auto upgrade for the message sender, for fallback functionality to upgrade tokens on receipt. The only reason a user would want to call this function is to modify behaviour *after* this contract has been updated, thus allowing choice.

params._autoUpgrade: Whether the tokens should be automatically upgraded when sent to this contract.

setByfrostNetwork(uint256,uint256,addres.details: Set by the owner, this functions sets it such that this contract was deployed on a Byfrost arm of the Shyft Network (on Ethereum for example). With this is a token grant that this contract should make to a specific distribution contract (ie. in the case of the initial Shyft Network launch, we have a small allocation originating on the Ethereum network).

params._bip32X_type: The Bip32X type that represents the synthetic tokens that will be allocated.
params._distributionContract: The public address of the distribution contract, that the tokens are allocated for.
params._tokenAmount: The amount of tokens to be allocated.

returns.result: | 2 = set byfrost as origin    | 1 = already set byfrost origin    | 0 = not owner

setLockOnlyAcceptsKycInputPermanently().details: Gets whether the user has set Accepts Kyc Input.

returns.result: | true = set lock for onlyAcceptsKycInput    | false = already set lock for onlyAcceptsKycInput

setOnlyAcceptsKycInput(bool).details: Sets whether to accept only Kyc Input in the future.

params._onlyAcceptsKycInputValue: Whether to accept only Kyc Input.

returns.result: | true = updated onlyAcceptsKycInput    | false = cannot modify onlyAcceptsKycInput, as it is locked permanently by user

setPrimaryNetwork().details: Set by the owner, this function sets it such that this contract was deployed on the primary Shyft Network. No further calls to setByfrostNetwork may be made.

returns.result: | 2 = set primary network    | 1 = already set byfrost origin    | 0 = not owner

setShyftCacheGraphAddress(address).details: Links Shyft CacheGraph to this contract's function flow.

params._shyftCacheGraphAddress: The smart contract address for the Shyft CacheGraph that should be linked.

returns.result: | 0: not owner    | 1: set shyft cache graph address

setShyftKycContractRegistryAddress(addre.details: Sets the Shyft Kyc Contract Registry address, so this contract can be upgraded.

params._addr: The Shyft Kyc Contract Registry address to set to.

returns._0: returns true if the function passes, otherwise reverts if the message sender is not the owner (deployer) of this contract.

symbol().details: Gets the symbol of the token.

tokenFallback(address,uint256,bytes).details: Transfers assets to destination, with ERC20 functionality. (basic ERC20 functionality, but blocks transactions if Only Accepts Kyc Input is set to true.)

params._data: The bytes data of any ERC223 transfer function.

returns.ok: returns true if the checks pass and there are enough allowed + actual tokens to transfer to the recipient.

setByfrostNetwork(uint256,uint256,addres.notice: | for created kyc contracts on other chains, they can be instantiated with specific bip32X_type amounts         | (for example, the shyft distribution contract on eth vs. shyft native)         |  '  uint256 bip32X_type = uint256(keccak256(abi.encodePacked(nativeBip32X_type, _erc20ContractAddress)));         |  '  bip32X_type = uint256(keccak256(abi.encodePacked(nativeBip32X_type, msg.sender)));         | the bip32X_type is formed by the hash of the native bip32x type (which is unique per-platform, as it depends on         | the deployed contract address) - byfrost only touches non-replay networks.         | so the formula for the bip32X_type would be HASH [ byfrost main chain bip32X_type ] & [ byfrost main chain kyc contract address ]         | these minted tokens are given to the distribution contract for further distribution. This is all this contract         | needs to know about the distribution contract.
